saliva to moisten food","Formation of food bolus by the tongue","Peristaltic waves moving food through the oesophagus","Voluntary propulsion of food to the posterior tongue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevation of soft palate and closure of larynx with coordinated muscle contractions\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the pharyngeal phase of swallowing. This phase involves multiple protective mechanisms to prevent aspiration and ensure safe passage of food.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of food bolus by the tongue\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during the oral preparatory phase of swallowing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVoluntary propulsion of food to the posterior tongue\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the oral phase of swallowing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of saliva to moisten food\u003C/strong\u003E - This is part of the oral preparatory phase of swallowing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeristaltic waves moving food through the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the oesophageal phase of swallowing\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pharyngeal phase involves elevation of the soft palate to prevent nasal regurgitation, elevation of the larynx and closure of the epiglottis to protect the airway, and coordinated contraction of pharyngeal constrictors to move the food bolus downward.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pharyngeal phase of swallowing involves elevation of the soft palate, closure of the larynx, and coordinated muscle contractions.","Multiple protective mechanisms prevent aspiration during swallowing including laryngeal elevation and epiglottic closure.","The swallowing centre in the medulla coordinates input from multiple cranial nerves to ensure safe passage of food."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17316"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:02:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:03:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10006"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p